Minister of Information and Culture, Alhaji Lai Mohammed, has described Government College, Keffi, as a great model for the unity of Nigeria as envisaged by the nation’s founding fathers. The minister stated this at the 70th Anniversary of the College in Keffi, Nasarawa State yesterday. Alhaji Lai Mohammed said if Nigerians would allow themselves to be guided by the Keffi Model, the present atmosphere of disunity at all levels such as religious, ethnic and  regional would have disappeared and peace would return to the nation. He disclosed that in his time only the very best from the 13 Provinces in the North made it to Government College, Keffi and not by any consideration. He stressed that in the school, religion, ethnicity and social status did not matter but rather one’s  academic prowess. The minister explained that the school was also a leveler where children of peasants mixed freely with the children of the rich. Alhaji Mohammed further said when he was a student, the most important day for them in school  was ‘Ash Wednesday’, because they would be served fish. He maintained that some Christian students also fasted along with those of them who were Muslims during the Ramadan. Alhaji Lai Mohammed implored Nigerians to emulate and revive the ‘Keffi spirit deemphasizing ethnicity, religion and social status and co-exist as Nigerians. The dignitaries who graced the occasion included the governor of Nasarawa State, Alhaji Abdullahi Sule; the Emir of Keffi, Alhaji Shehu Chindo Yamusa; the former registrar of JAMB, Prof. Bello Salim and retired Supreme Court Justice James Ogebe.